properties.Title: freezing rain warning in effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Freezing rain is expected or occurring. Freezing drizzle mixed at times with freezing rain will persist tonight then taper off on Sunday. Surfaces such as highways, roads, walkways and parking lots may become icy and slippery. Take extra care when walking or driving in affected areas. Freezing Rain Warnings are issued when rain falling in sub-zero temperatures creates ice build-up and icy surfaces. Environment Canada meteorologists will update alerts as required. Stay up to date with Weatheradio or your local media. Email reports of severe weather to weatherNLWO@ec.gc.ca or call 1-877-815-9900. You may tweet reports using the hashtag #NLwx.

properties.Title: blizzard warning in effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and visibility frequently near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. A low pressure system over Northern Nunavik will track toward the Labrador Sea on Sunday. In its wake, blizzard conditions will develop over these regions beginning midday Sunday. If you do travel and become lost, remain where you are until the blizzard has passed. Protect yourself from wind, cold and disorientation by staying sheltered, indoors or with your vehicle. Public Safety Canada encourages everyone to make an emergency plan and get an emergency kit with drinking water, food, medicine, a first-aid kit and a flashlight. For information on emergency plans and kits go to http://www.getprepared.gc.ca/ Blizzard Warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 4 hours. Environment Canada meteorologists will update alerts as required. Please continue to monitor your local media or Weatheradio for further updates. If you would like to report severe weather, you can call 1-800-361-0233 or send an email to tempsviolent.quebec@ec.gc.ca. You may also tweet reports of severe weather to #meteoqc.

properties.Title: wind warning in effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. A low pressure system over Northern Nunavik will track toward the Labrador Sea on Sunday. In its wake, high winds gusting to 100 km/h will develop over Quaqtaq late Sunday. Please note that these winds will also give blizzard conditions. Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. Be prepared to adjust your driving with changing road conditions due to high winds. Avoid wooded areas to prevent injury from falling trees or branches. Campers should move to sturdy shelters. Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Environment Canada meteorologists will update alerts as required. Please continue to monitor your local media or Weatheradio for further updates. If you would like to report severe weather, you can call 1-800-361-0233 or send an email to tempsviolent.quebec@ec.gc.ca. You may also tweet reports of severe weather to #meteoqc.

properties.Title: blizzard warning in effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and visibility frequently near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. A strong eastward tracking low pressure system over far northern Quebec has generated snow and blowing snow with strong east winds at Cape Dorset. Visibilities in the 200 to 400 metre range this morning improved slightly during the day. Conditions are expected to deteriorate once again tonight as northerly winds strengthen. The blizzard should end Sunday morning as winds start to diminish. Travel is expected to be extremely hazardous due to reduced visibility. If you do travel and become lost, remain where you are until the blizzard has passed. Protect yourself from wind, cold and disorientation by staying sheltered, indoors or with your vehicle. Public Safety Canada encourages everyone to make an emergency plan and get an emergency kit with drinking water, food, medicine, a first-aid kit and a flashlight. For information on emergency plans and kits go to http://www.getprepared.gc.ca/ Blizzard Warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 4 hours. Environment Canada meteorologists will update alerts as required. Please continue to monitor your local media or Weatheradio for further updates. If you would like to report severe weather, you can call 1-800-239-0484 or send an email to storm@ec.gc.ca or tweet reports to #NUStorm.

properties.Title: wind warning in effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Strong winds that may cause damage are expected or occurring. A low pressure system over Northern Nunavik will track toward the Labrador Sea on Sunday. In its wake, high winds gusting to 100 km/h will develop over Quaqtaq late Sunday. Please note that these winds will also give blizzard conditions. Damage to buildings, such as to roof shingles and windows, may occur. Loose objects may be tossed by the wind and cause injury or damage. Be prepared to adjust your driving with changing road conditions due to high winds. Avoid wooded areas to prevent injury from falling trees or branches. Campers should move to sturdy shelters. Wind warnings are issued when there is a significant risk of damaging winds. Environment Canada meteorologists will update alerts as required. Please continue to monitor your local media or Weatheradio for further updates. If you would like to report severe weather, you can call 1-800-361-0233 or send an email to tempsviolent.quebec@ec.gc.ca. You may also tweet reports of severe weather to #meteoqc.

properties.Title: blizzard warning in effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Blizzard conditions with gusty winds and visibility frequently near zero in snow and blowing snow are expected or occurring. A strong low pressure system tracking east over northeastern Hudson Bay has produced snow and blowing snow with strong northeast winds at Coral Harbour. Visibilities around 400 metres are expected to persist until around midnight, after which time they should begin a gradual improvement as the low pulls away from the area. Travel is expected to be extremely hazardous due to reduced visibility. If you do travel and become lost, remain where you are until the blizzard has passed. Protect yourself from wind, cold and disorientation by staying sheltered, indoors or with your vehicle. Public Safety Canada encourages everyone to make an emergency plan and get an emergency kit with drinking water, food, medicine, a first-aid kit and a flashlight. For information on emergency plans and kits go to http://www.getprepared.gc.ca/ Blizzard Warnings are issued when widespread reduced visibilities of 400 metres or less are expected for at least 4 hours. Environment Canada meteorologists will update alerts as required. Please continue to monitor your local media or Weatheradio for further updates. If you would like to report severe weather, you can call 1-800-239-0484 or send an email to storm@ec.gc.ca or tweet reports to #NUStorm.
